  "interpretation": {
    "headline": "YES: Bundle sessions have 8.9x lower coordination overhead per finding (2.877 commits/lesson vs 25.6). Throughput: bundles produce 34.8x more lessons/session (3.41 vs 0.098). Per-lane efficiency: bundles produce 3.6x lessons/lane (0.355 vs 0.098). Robustness (excl outliers >20 lanes): 2.64 L/session, 0.517 L/lane. Effect holds after removing S186 (340 lanes) and other extreme sessions.",
    "efficiency_direction": "Bundle HIGHER lessons/lane (0.355 vs 0.098)",
    "throughput_direction": "Bundle 34.8x more lessons/session (3.41 vs 0.098)",
    "overhead_per_finding": "Bundle LOWER overhead (2.877 commits/lesson vs 25.6)",
    "l812_comparison": "L-812 (S397, n=141 sessions, 989 lanes): solo 0.18 L/session, bundle 1.85 L/session (10x), Cohen d=1.15. Bundle overhead 2x (1.92 rows/lesson vs 1.0). Current analysis (n=156 sessions, 1059 lanes): solo 0.098 L/session, bundle 3.41 L/session (34.8x). Direction consistent with L-812: throughput dominance, higher per-lane overhead in absolute terms.",
    "key_findings": [
      "Bundle sessions produce 34.8x more lessons per session",
      "Bundle per-lane efficiency is 3.6x solo",
      "Bundle coordination overhead is 0.11x solo (commits/lesson)",
      "Bundle merged rate 66.4% vs solo 92.2% (lane-level)",
      "Session-level majority-merged: bundle 85.7% vs solo 92.2%",
      "Effect robust to outlier exclusion (>20 lanes): 26.94x L/session ratio",
      "Cohen's d for lessons/session: 0.595",
      "DOMEX-era (S300+) ratio: 11.43x L/session",
      "Sweet spot: 7-11 lanes/session maximizes L/lane (0.67-1.55) \u2014 above 12, efficiency drops sharply"
    ],
    "answer": "Bundling reduces per-finding coordination overhead measured as commits/lesson (2.877 vs 25.6, 8.9x reduction). The throughput advantage is even larger: bundles produce 34.8x more lessons/session. However, bundle merged rate is lower (66.4% vs 92.2%), meaning bundles open more lanes that get abandoned \u2014 the coordination cost appears as wasted lanes rather than wasted commits. Net: bundling is overwhelmingly better for throughput and moderately better for per-finding overhead, at the cost of lower per-lane success rate."
  },
